  "prompt": "How do you determine the Lewis structure of SO2?",
  "response": "To determine the Lewis structure of sulfur dioxide (SO\u2082), follow these steps:\n\n1. **Count the total valence electrons**: \n   - Sulfur (S) is in group 16 of the periodic table and has 6 valence electrons.\n   - Each oxygen (O) atom, also in group 16, has 6 valence electrons. Since there are two oxygen atoms, you have: \n     \\[\n     6 \\, (\\text{from } S) + 2 \\times 6 \\, (\\text{from } 2 \\, O) = 6 + 12 = 18 \\, \\text{valence electrons}.\n     \\]\n\n2. **Draw the skeletal structure**: \n   - Place the sulfur atom in the center because it is less electronegative than oxygen. Connect the two oxygen atoms to the sulfur atom with single bonds:\n     ```\n       O\n       |\n       S\n       |\n       O\n     ```\n\n3. **Distribute the remaining electrons**: \n   - Each S-O bond uses 2 electrons, so for two bonds, that accounts for 4 of the total 18 valence electrons:\n     \\[\n     18 - 4 = 14 \\, \\text{electrons remaining}.\n     \\]\n   - Place three lone pairs (6 electrons) around each oxygen atom to complete their octets:\n     ```\n         O:   (lone pairs not shown)\n         ||\n       :S:\n         ||\n         O:\n     ```\n\n4. **Check the octets and adjust as needed**: \n   - In the current structure, the O atoms have complete octets (8 electrons each), but sulfur only has 4 electrons from the bonds. Therefore, we can create a double bond between sulfur and each oxygen to give sulfur a complete octet:\n     ```\n         O\n        ||\n        S\n        ||\n         O\n     ```\n\n5. **Final structure**: \n   - Check that each atom has a complete octet. Sulfur has 8 electrons (4 from two double bonds) and both oxygen atoms have 8 electrons (from the double bonds and no lone pairs). The final Lewis structure of SO\u2082 is:\n     ```\n         O\n        ||\n        S\n        ||\n         O\n     ```\n   - The final check shows that the total number of valence electrons used is 18, verifying that the structure adheres to the rules of Lewis structures.\n\nThis Lewis structure indicates that sulfur is the central atom bonded to two oxygen atoms with double bonds.",
